11.45 PM: Singer John Legend has criticised US President Donald Trumps order saying America has to be better than that. Los Angeles is the home of so many immigrants, so many creative people, so many dreamers, and those of us who work in this business have the privilege of shaping how the rest of the world perceives this country we love, Legend said. 
 
11:35 AM: Despite the massive outpouring of outrage across the world and clearly unfazed US President Donald Trump today defended his order. He said, Its working out very nicely. You see it at the airports, you see it all over. Trump, however added, Its not a Muslim ban, but we are totally prepared. 
 
11:08 AM: People large in numbers have gathered at the John F Kennedy International Airport in New York and other airports around USA, protesting President Donald Trumps ban on Muslim immigrants and refugees. These protests began at Terminal-4 of New York airport soon after immigration authorities detained 11 refugees who were already in transit. Earlier, Iran, reacting strongly to Trumps decision, banned the entry of US citizens in Iran. 
 
10.45 AM: According to CNN, a federal judge in New York while issuing a stay order that blocks the deportation of people stranded at the US airports under President Donald Trumps executive orders said, The petitioners have a strong likelihood of success in establishing that the removal of the petitioner and other similarly situated violates their due process and equal protection guaranteed by the United States Constitution. 
 
10.35 AM: New ban on US travel for nationals of seven Middle Eastern countries has also put the airline industry in a quandary as flight crew from those states stand barred too from entering. US Customs and Border Protection (CBP) has said that passport-holders from states such as Iran and Iraq, including cabin crew, will be barred entry to the United States, IATA said in an email. 
 
